# Playwright Actions
1️⃣ What are Actions in Playwright?
Actions are operations performed on web page elements during automation
Playwright actions simulate real user interactions such as:
    1. Clicking a button
    2. typing a test
    3. Selecting dropdown values
    4. Checking checkboxes
    5. Uploading files
    6. Hovering on elements
👉 In simple terms:
    Action = Interact with an web element
Example
-------
    page.locator("#login").click()
Here the action is click()

2️⃣ Why Actions are Important
Actions are important because they allow automation scripts to interact with the applications like a real user.
Actions are used to:
    1. Perform UI operations
    2. Simulate real user behavior
    3. Execute workflows (login , purchase , seach)
    4. Validate applications functionality
Without actions, tests cannot interact with the application UI.

3️⃣ Playwright Actionability Checks
Before performing any action, Playwright performs automatic checks to ensure the element is ready.
These checks include:
    1. Element is visible
    2. Element is stable (not moving)
    3. Element is enabled
    4. Element is receiving events
    5. Locator resolves to exactly one element
If checks fail , Playwright auto-waits until conditions are satisfied.
This reduces flaky tests.

4️⃣ Commonly Used Actions in Playwright
    1️⃣ click()
    Used to click a button , link or element.
    Example:
        page.locator("#login").click()
    
    Example:
        page.get_by_role("button" , name ="Submit").click()
    
    Usecases:
        1. Submit forms
        2. Click buttons
        3. Navigate pages
    
    2️⃣ dblclick()
    Used to double click an element
    Example:
        page.locator("#file").dblclick()
    
    Use cases:
        1. File section
        2. Open folders
    
    3️⃣ fill()
    Used to enter text into input fields
    Example:
        page.locator("#username").fill("admin")
    Example:
        page.get_by_label("Password").fill("admin123")
    
    Use cases:
        1. Login forms
        2. Seach fields
        3. Registration forms
    
    4️⃣ type()
    Used to type characters sequantially.
    Example:
        page.locator("#search").type("playwright")
    
    Difference:
        Method & Behavior
        -----------------
        1. fill() -> Replaces existing text
        2. type() -> Types character by character
    
    5️⃣ press()
    Used to press keyboard keys
    Example:
        page.locator("#search").press("Enter")

    Example:
        page.keyboard.press("Escape")
    
    Common Keys:
    ------------
    1. Enter
    2. Tab
    3. Escape
    4. ArrowUP
    5. ArrowDown

    6️⃣ check()
    Used to select a checkbox
    Examples:
        page.locator("#remember").check()
    
    Use cases:
        1. Agree terms
        2. Select options
    
    7️⃣ uncheck()
    Used to unselect a checkbox
    Examples:
        page.locator("#remember").uncheck()
    
    8️⃣ select_option()
    Used to select values from dropdown menus
    Examples:
        page.locator("#country").select_option("India")
    
    Example using value:
        page.locator("#country").select_option(value = "IN")

    Example using label:
        page.locator("#country").select_option(label = "India")
    
    9️⃣ hover()
    Used to hover the mouse over an element
    Example:
        page.locator("#menu").hover()
    
    Use cases:
        1. Open dropdown menus
        2. Display tooltips
    
    🔟 drag_to()
    Used to drag an element and drops it to another element.
    Example:
        page.locator("#item").drag_to(page.locator("#cart"))

    Use cases:
        1. Drag and drop UI
        2. Moving elements
    
    1️⃣1️⃣ set_input_files()
    Used to upload files
    Example:
        page.locator("#upload").set_input_files("testfile.pdf")
    
    Example multiple files:
        page.locator("#upload").set_input_files(["file1.txt" , "file2.txt"])

    1️⃣2️⃣ clear()
    Used to clear input field text
    Example:
        page.locator("#username").clear()
    
    1️⃣3️⃣ focus()
    Used to focus an element
    Example:
        page.locator("#email").focus()
    
    1️⃣4️⃣ scroll_into_view_if_needed()
    Scrolls the page until the element becomes visible.
    Example:
        page.locator("#submit").scroll_into_view_if_needed()
    
    1️⃣5️⃣ Screenshot Action
    Playwright allows capturing screenshots
    Example:
        page.screenshot(path = "page.png")
    
    Element screenshot:
        page.locator("#login").screenshot(path = "page.png")
    
    1️⃣6️⃣ Keyboard Actions
    Keyboard operations can be performed using page.keyboard()
    Example:
        page.keyboard.type("Hello")
    
    Example:
        page.keyboard.type("Enter")

    Shortcut example:
        page.keyboard.press("Control+A")
    
    1️⃣7️⃣ Mouse Actions
    Mouse interactions can be performed using page.mouse()
    Example:
        page.mouse.click(200 , 300)
    
    Example:
        page.mouse.move(100 , 200)

    Examples:
        page.mouse.down()
        page.mouse.up()
    
    1️⃣8️⃣ Force Actions
    Sometimes elements may not pass actionability checks.
    In that case , force option can be used.
    Example:
        page.locator("#submit").click(force=True)
    ⚠️ Use only when necessary.

    1️⃣9️⃣ Timeout for Actions
    Actions can have custom timeouts
    Example:
        page.locator("#login").click(timeout=5000)
    This waits 5 seconds before failing.

    2️⃣0️⃣ Example Login Test Using Actions
    def test_login(page):
        page.goto("https://example.com")

        page.get_by_label("Username").fill("admin")
        page.get_by_label("Password").fill("admin123")

        page.get_by_role("button" name = "login").click()
        page.get_by_text("Dashboard")
    
    Actions used:
        1. click()
        2. fill()

    2️⃣2️⃣ Difference Between Actions and Assertions
    Actions & Assertions
    ---------------------
    1. Perform operatiosn -> validate results
    2. click() , fill() -> expect()
    3. interact with UI -> Verify UI

    Example:
        page.locator("#login").click()
    
    Assertion
        expect(page.locator("#dashboard")).to_be_visible()
    
    
    
